>>55651826
You use em-dashes to set off moments when the narrator explains things to the reader but it's still part of the story. Preferably short passages since em-dashes don't indicate beginning and end so if they're long or used twice in a long sentence the reader may lose track of beginning and end. Contrast that to parentheses, which is when the explanation is giving non-story information to the reader.

Anyway, this paragraph is shit but the em-dashes aren't the problem. It's the ellipsis that isn't either indicating lost text of the narrator (as it would be here) or spoke words trailing off or hesitating (as it would be inside of quote marks). It's apparently trying to indicate the narrator hesitating; why? Because it's sloppy word salad after that. I'm going to try to guess at what you're intending here:

>Standing beside her blinded father and holding the battered remains of her droid, it would be the last time that Lop would see her sister. The Yasaburo Clan fled their ancestral home, a family torn apart by the Empire, forced to part ways by cuts and slashes.

Save awkward sentence structures, halted phrases, and fragments for dialog unless it's serving a plot point or protecting a plot twist (while hinting at or foreshadowing it) because your reader relies on the narrator to be clear and easy to follow, not to try to be a drama queen himself. Drama is for the players to portray.

>>55651826
To my knowledge, a dash is meant to be used to separate an aside that has relevant information but doesn't warrant its own full sentence. It doesn't have to, but it's best used by providing information which then directly leads into the next sentence/paragraph i.e. "The trip north would take three days - by air. We would never make it on foot."

You can use a dash break in the middle of a sentence in the same way - just like you did in the sentence that guy linked - if you separate the aside with dashes on both sides. The problem you had there wasn't the dash break in and of itself, it was that you just chained ways of extending a sentence together (ellipses and then a dash break in the middle of the sentence) until it was way too long to reasonably read out loud.
It'd be better off just being split up, as an example you could do something like
>Standing by her blinded father, holding the battered remains of her droid… It was the last time Lop saw her sister alive. They'd parted ways in cuts and slashes, their family torn apart by the Empire - the start of a years-long exodus as Lop and the YasaburÅ Clan fled their ancestral home.

In first or third person limited, a dash break can also be readily used to separate statements and supporting logic. However, this should be done sparingly, and only in action scenes to keep up pressure without losing any beats i.e. "He had no hope of beating her in a fight - she was just too fast."

I like to think that waifurs would exhibit some aspects of behavior and preferences that are like those of the animals to which they're similar. But it would be cute and not extreme. Your fox waifur might really like chicken and eggs, and enjoy grooming and being groomed. She might be clever and curious. Cat waifur might like seafood, might be very physically affectionate, might purr when she's happy, but wouldn't yowl or have a compulsion to bury her poop. Dog waifur might like a meat-heavy diet, might be very excited to see you when you come home, might be loyal and protective, but she's not going to yell at squirrels, or chase cars. And so on.

>>55663476
Laser focused on two characters, but 23k of loose ends all hitting at once. So they're trapped in an elevator and talking about all the stuff they never talked about before for two and a half hours waiting on the fire department to pry the doors open?

I'll put it this way: Can you summarize the gist of the chapter in a short paragraph and does it sound interesting when you do?

Example: "Lead character meets the supporting cast, kinda gets in trouble with them, but one of them thinks that person deserves a break. Joining their group destabilizes it which will be a problem in a chapter or two."

That's a chapter with one arc and no B. Intro (encounter), rising (trouble), climax (decision), falling (acceptance), and resolution (set up pending conflict).

Does your 23k have a structure with just really dense acts? Or is it doing a quick intro, an eternal rising where way too much comes into play, a mess of a climax where too many things should be coming to a head to really focus on, then falling has such a mess to clean up that you can't ever get to your resolution?

If it's like what I imagine it could be, you might need that B-plot. Something that can be a nagging interruption that forces these deeper-into-things to go one at a time and make sure that at least one resolves before a third is introduced. Might be able to churn a few at a time in say three sets and make three chapters out of it about 9k each. Even if that's smaller than your usual chapter size, that contrast will put emphasis on these being chapters that investigate past mysteries rather than introduce new and developing issues.
